'''Imperial College Healthcare NHS Trust''' is an  [[NHS trust]] based in [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]. It is the second largest<ref>http://www.bartshealth.nhs.uk/about-us/</ref> <ref>http://www.nhs.uk/services/trusts/overview/defaultview.aspx?id=34604</ref>NHS trust in England<ref name=tele942011>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/8438898/Englands-biggest-hospital-trust-faces-40m-budget-black-hole.html|title=England's biggest hospital trust faces £40m budget black hole|accessdate=28 April 2011|publisher=The Telegraph|date=9 April 2011}}</ref> and together with [[Imperial College London]] forms an [[academic health science centre]].

Imperial College Healthcare was formed in October 2007 by the merger of Hammersmith Hospitals NHS Trust and St Mary's NHS Trust and their integration with [[Imperial College Faculty of Medicine]]. It currently manages five hospitals: [[Charing Cross Hospital]]; [[Hammersmith Hospital]]; [[Queen Charlotte's and Chelsea Hospital]]; [[St Mary's Hospital, London|St Mary's Hospital]] and [[Western Eye Hospital]].

In 2009/10 Imperial College Healthcare had a turnover of £900 million, employed approximately 10,460 people and treated over one million patients.<ref name=annrep200910>{{cite web|url=http://www.imperial.nhs.uk/prdcons/groups/public/@corporate/@communications/documents/doc/id_026111.pdf|title=Annual Report 2009/10|accessdate=28 April 2011|publisher=Imperial College Healthcare NHS Trust}}</ref> The Trust's chief executive is Mark Davies. The chair of the Trust was [[Christopher Tugendhat, Baron Tugendhat|Lord Tugendhat]] from its inception in October 2007 until December 2011 when he was succeeded by [[Richard Sykes (biochemist)|Sir Richard Sykes]].

==History==
Imperial College Healthcare was formed on 1 October 2007 by the merger of Hammersmith Hospitals NHS Trust and St Mary's NHS Trust with [[Imperial College|Imperial College London]] Faculty of Medicine.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23414567-super-trust-will-offer-quicker-cures.do|title=Super-trust will offer quicker cures|accessdate=28 April 2011|publisher=London Evening Standard|date=1 October 2007}}</ref> In July 2008 Imperial College Healthcare announced that it would be launching a pilot scheme to reward medical teams with bonuses for successful operations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/7516296.stm|title='Rewards for medics' excellence'|accessdate=28 April 2011|publisher=BBC News|date=20 July 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/health/article4364439.ece|title=Surgeons set for pay bonuses if their operations are successful|accessdate=28 April 2011|publisher=The Times|date=20 July 2008}}</ref> In January 2009 the results of a study were published in which researchers had successfully captured [[Magnetic resonance imaging|MRI]] images of bleeding inside the hearts of 15 Imperial College Healthcare patients who had suffered a heart attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1122667/A-patients-bleeding-heart-pictured-time.html|title=A patient's bleeding heart is pictured for the first time|accessdate=28 April 2011|publisher=Daily Mail|date=19 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/4292153/First-pictures-inside-a-heart-attack.html|title=First pictures inside a heart attack|accessdate=28 April 2011|publisher=The Telegraph|date=20 January 2009}}</ref> In November 2009 a team led by Professor Paul Abel of Imperial College Healthcare performed the first removal of a rectal cancer using ultrasound.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8380812.stm|title=Rectal cancer tumour destroyed by ultrasound is a first |accessdate=28 April 2011|publisher=BBC News|date=26 November 2009}}</ref> In April 2011 it was reported that Imperial College Healthcare had an underlying financial deficit and faced a potential gap of £40 million between income and expenditure in 2011/12.<ref name=tele942011/>

==Organisation==
[[File:Hammersmith Hospital in 2009.jpg|thumb|right|[[Hammersmith Hospital]]]]

===Clinical structure===
The clinical services of Imperial College Healthcare are organised into seven clinical programme groups:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imperial.nhs.uk/aboutus/ourorganisation/index.htm|title=Our organisation|accessdate=1 May 2011|publisher=Imperial College Healthcare NHS Trust}}</ref>

*Medicine
*Surgery and cancer
*Specialist services
*Circulation sciences and renal medicine
*Women’s and children's
*Clinical and investigative services
*Preventative interventional public health

===Finances===
[[File:Western Eye Hospital.jpeg|thumb|right|The [[Western Eye Hospital]]]]
In 2009/10 Imperial College Healthcare had a total income of £900.23 million, of which £680.18 million was from patient care activities and £220.05 million was from other operating revenue.<ref name=annrep200910/> In the same year it had operating expenses of £868.84 million, capital expenditure of £66.79 million and generated an operating surplus of £31.4 million.<ref name=annrep200910/>

As at 31 March 2010 Imperial College Healthcare had total assets of £837.80 million, total assets less current liabilities of £729.86 million and total assets employed of £697.1 million.<ref name=annrep200910/>

===Staff===

During 2009/10 Imperial College Healthcare employed an average of 10,464 people:<ref name=annrep200910/>
*Administration and estates staff - 2,575
*Healthcare assistants and other support staff - 955
*Medical and dental staff - 1,675
*Nursing, midwifery and health visiting staff - 3,622
*Scientific, therapeutic and technical staff - 1,418
*Other staff - 219

==Research==
In partnership with Imperial College London, Imperial College Healthcare is a major centre for medical research.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imperial.nhs.uk/research/about/index.htm|title=Imperial College Healthcare Research|accessdate=28 April 2011|publisher=Imperial College Healthcare NHS Trust}}</ref> It is also part of one of only five [[National Institute for Health Research]] Comprehensive Biomedical Research Centres to be established by the NHS in England.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=207821&sectioncode=26|title=South secures research cash
|accessdate=29 April 2011|publisher=Times Higher Education|date=16 February 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nihr.ac.uk/infrastructure/Pages/infrastructure_biomedical_research_centres.aspx|title=Biomedical Research Centres|accessdate=29 April 2011|publisher=National Institute for Health Research}}</ref>

